'''Influenza A virus subtype H6N1''', also known as '''H6N1''', is a subtype of the [[influenza A virus]]. It has only infected one person, a woman in Taiwan, who recovered.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Yuan | first1 = J. | last2 = Zhang | first2 = L. | last3 = Kan | first3 = X. | last4 = Jiang | first4 = L. | last5 = Yang | first5 = J. | last6 = Guo | first6 = Z. | last7 = Ren | first7 = Q. | doi = 10.1093/cid/cit479 | title = Origin and Molecular Characteristics of a Novel 2013 Avian Influenza A(H6N1) Virus Causing Human Infection in Taiwan | journal = Clinical Infectious Diseases | volume = 57 | issue = 9 | pages = 1367–1368 | year = 2013 | pmid =  23881153| pmc = }}</ref> Known to infect [[Eurasian teal]], it is closely related to subtype [[H5N1]].<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Hoffmann | first1 = E. | last2 = Stech | first2 = J. | last3 = Leneva | first3 = I. | last4 = Krauss | first4 = S. | last5 = Scholtissek | first5 = C. | last6 = Chin | first6 = P. S. | last7 = Peiris | first7 = M. | last8 = Shortridge | first8 = K. F. | last9 = Webster | first9 = R. G. | doi = 10.1128/JVI.74.14.6309-6315.2000 | title = Characterization of the Influenza a Virus Gene Pool in Avian Species in Southern China: Was H6N1 a Derivative or a Precursor of H5N1? | journal = Journal of Virology | volume = 74 | issue = 14 | pages = 6309–6315 | year = 2000 | pmid =  10864640| pmc =112136 }}</ref>

