'''''The Global 2000 Report to the President''''' <ref>[[Gerald O. Barney]], Study Director, The Global 2000 Report to the President, US Government Printing Office, Washington, DC, 1980</ref> was a 1980 report on [[sustainable development|sustainable societal development]], commissioned by President [[Jimmy Carter]] on May 23, 1977.  The report was released at a press conference in the White House on July 24, 1980. The report sold 1.5 million copies in 9 languages. There were many [http://www.geraldbarney.com/G2000Page.html editions of the report].

The Global 2000 project was directed by [[Gerald O. Barney]], and the main conclusion of the report was:  

::If present trends continue, the world in 2000 will be more crowded, and more vulnerable to disruption than the world we live in now. Serious stresses involving population, resources, and environment are clearly visible ahead. Despite greater material output, the world's people will be poorer in many ways than they are today.<ref>[[Gerald O. Barney]], Study Director, The Global 2000 Report to the President, Vol. I, US Government Printing Office, Washington, DC, 1980.</ref>

The Global 2000 Report was based on the best data and models available from 14 participating government agencies plus the [[World Bank]].  Projections were made using  [[computer model]]s.  {{cns|date=April 2018|text=No other country has ever undertaken a comparable study of the future of the world.}}

The Global 2000 project produced a report, but the Global 2000 project was more than a report.  It was the {{cns|date=April 2018|text=first (and to date the only)}} effort by a nation to prepare a 20-year outlook on probable changes in the world’s population, resources, economy, and environment.  {{cns|date=April 2018|text=It was the first and only}} time the long-term global professionals of an entire national government were assembled as a team to look at the future of the entire world.  {{cns|date=April 2018|text=It was the first and only}} time that sector-specific global policy models (population, energy, agriculture, forestry, economy, minerals, non-fuel minerals, water, etc.) were assembled and consistency assessed as the “foundation for longer-term planning” that they in fact are.<ref>"Analysis of the Projection Tools: The Government's Global Model," Chapters 14-23, Gerald O. Barney, Study Director, The Global 200 Report to the President, Vol. II, US Government Printing Office, Washington, DC, 1980</ref> It was {{cns|date=April 2018|text=the first and only}} time that all previous global studies were assembled and reviewed for their insights and recommendations.  It was {{cns|date=April 2018|text=the first and only}} time that a nation made an assessment of all of its previous efforts to take a long-term view of anything.<ref>"Lessons from the Past," Appendix A, Global 2000 Report to the President, Vol. II, US Government Printing Office, Washington, DC, 1980</ref>

Global 2000 was not the first computer-based global study.  The first computer-based global study, ''[[The Limits to Growth]]''<ref>Meadows, Meadows, Randers, and Behrens, The Limits to Growth, Universe Books, New York, 1972</ref> was published in 1972.  ''Limits'' questioned growth as the answer to all development and social problems and started a global discussion of [[global warming]], energy [[scarcity]], human [[population growth]], plant and species extinctions {{Clarify|date=July 2011}}, genetic diversity {{Clarify|date=July 2011}}, and a global economic system based on unlimited human wants in contrast to [[Earth]]'s finite resources, etc. {{Citation needed|date=July 2011}}  {{cns|date=April 2018|text=Nothing in the Global 2000 report refutes or contradicts the conclusions of ''Limits to Growth''.}}

